The ranges are low. China will certainly sell more than 40M vehicles in the forecast period. March 2021 new energy was nearly 10% of production. The stated goal for 2025 is 20%. Simple linear progression with conservative assumptions easily beats 4M units.

China ha sido de los países con más incentivos a la compra de autos eléctricos en todo el mundo, además de dominar el mercado global en la producción de autos. Potencias como Estados Unidos o Europa, quedan cortos ya sea en los subsidios que entregan o en la menor capacidad de producción. GM lanzó hace poco el nuevo modelo de eléctrico el Hong Guang Mini, un auto con un costo de tan solo 4.000 USD. El mercado en China no se compara con el estadounidense o europeo, quienes prefieren autos más grandes y lujosos. China por su parte apunta a autos pequeños y eficientes, y por lo tanto menos exigentes. Sin embargo, el gigante asiático ya cuenta con marcas que buscan abarcar este mercado más lujoso con marcas como NIO, quienes apuntan competir con Tesla en el segmento de autos eléctricos de alta gama. Esta última ya cuenta con sus propias fábricas en China, cuyo gobierno lo recibió con beneficios exclusivos, entendiendo el valor que tiene Tesla dentro del mercado. China tiene todas las de ganar en esta carrera de los EV's, si las otras potencias quieren estar a la altura les falta mucho por avanzar.

I think the Wuhling Mini EV is going to be a BIG seller and could push the numbers up all on its own: small, very affordable and with backing by three big players, it is going to sell in droves. Combined with a % shift towards NEVs and I am going slightly more bullish: Forecast 3.8-4.9M

The Chinese car market is reported to have seen 3.96mn new car sales in January+February 2021 alone. Under the rather conservative assumption this pace will apply for the whole period of this question, the total sales could exceed 55mn units in 2021 and 2022. In this context, 4.0mn represent roughly 7.3% of market share. However, China is expected to achieve an above-average market share in EVs compared to global market share figures, which I estimate to hit close to 8.0%. It is thus likely that, simply by the exceptional growth of the total market, government subsidies and competitive advantages of EV manufacturers, EVs will reach up to 6mn units until end-2022.

China has seen tremendous growth in NEV sales from 2016-2020. NEV sales have gone from just over 500,000 to 1.37 million in 2020. Average NEV sales for the last three years are now over 1.2 million. Beijing has an ambitious goal to have NEV sales reach 20% of vehicle sales by 2025, which seems like a long-shot (currently NEV sales are 5%). However, the continuation of national and local subsidies for NEV sales, along with a rebound in Chinese vehicle sales in 2021, put the outlook for NEV sales in a good position. CAAM expects growth to top 1.8 million in 2021. Seems a bit rosy but even a middle of the road estimate would put vehicle sales in 2021 in the 1.55 to 1.6 million units in 2021. Similar growth rates push that number to 1.8 million in 2022. I think for the two years combined we are looking at about 3.4 million, give or take. Given Beijings goals, it is not out of the realm those numbers get pushed significantly higher so we must account for that.

I probably underestimated the 2.2 / 2.8 scenario.

To me, it is likely that China really tries to reach it goals of 1/5 of the market which makes 5 millions of cars annually in 2025, so it has to increase by 3.5 millions over 5 years what makes roughly a 700k increasing per year. We could expect it to be a little bit exponential (though it slowed down in 2019 : https://www.jato.com/shanghai-2019-chinese-ev-demand-boosted-by-cheaper-cars/) , so I'd say that the next year should see an increase of 500k, and 2022 of 600k ==> 1.7 + 1.8 > 3.4

My P50 case is that of flattish sales, hence 1.2mln per year for two years, therefore I give it 40%. A growth case is one with 1.3-1.5mln in 2021 and 1.5-2mln in 2022, total range 2.8-3.5mln total, therefore I give it 43%, equal to but a bit higher than the flat case, with no reason to promote “growth” over “flat”. I give 10% to the “extra growth” case and 5% to the “exponential super growth case”, as both being more optimistic cases, which I’m not sure about. I’m leaving a mere 2% for the “decreased sales case”, which could be attributable to an unforeseen scenario, where electrification slows or takes a U turn for whatever reason.
I'm surprised that as a crowd we expect flat to negative growth in '21 and '22 combined. It just feels a little too "viewed through the lens of the present moment" for my tastes.

Chinese government has nominal pressure on car-makers to produce NEVs. But there's only so much consumenr demand. NEV sales have risen in fits and starts since 2015, but has never cracked the million-unit barrier. For it to rise above 2.2 M for 2 years, government underwriting will have to overcome consumer reluctance: historically, not an ideal bet.

This question is much harder than it's companion because there will be many more NEV's to choose from and competition will be fierce for market share, especially in 2022. With total annual car sales in the 16-20M/annually range in that timeframe will NEV's capture 10% of the market? I say yes by 2022. But what will 2021 look like? Go big.
